 “Microsoft Sentinel is a cloud-native SIEM and SOAR platform that centralizes security logs, correlates alerts, and enables automated response across the entire environment.”

Pause.

Then continue naturally.

---

### 🔹 Set the Context (Your Current Environment)

> “Today in our environment, we are running multiple security tools.
> We have CrowdStrike, Prisma, Carbon Black, and Microsoft Defender for Endpoint.
>
> Each of these tools collects logs and generates alerts.
> Each has its own portal.
> Each has its own backend server.
>
> So now we have alerts, events, and logs coming from multiple endpoints and multiple security platforms.”

---

### 🔹 Raise the Key Question

> “Now the question is — if every tool already has its own console, why do we need Sentinel?”

Pause. Look at audience.

---

### 🔹 Explain the Problem (Siloed Visibility)

> “The challenge is that each tool sees only its own part of the attack surface.
>
> CrowdStrike sees endpoint activity.
> Prisma sees cloud workloads.
> Carbon Black sees endpoint telemetry.
> MDE sees endpoint threats.
>
> But attackers don’t attack in silos.”

---

### 🔹 Small Attack Example (Very Important)

> “For example, imagine an attacker sends a phishing email.
>
> The user clicks the link — email logs capture it.
> The attacker steals credentials — Azure AD logs show suspicious login.
> The attacker logs into a server — server logs record access.
> Then a suspicious PowerShell runs — endpoint tool detects it.
>
> Now tell me — which single tool sees the full picture? when gone beyougn our endpoint in our case ”

Pause.

> “None of them.”

---

### 🔹 Introduce Sentinel’s Role

> “This is where Microsoft Sentinel comes in.
>
> Sentinel does not replace these tools.
> It sits above them.
>
> It ingests logs and alerts from all these platforms and correlates them in one centralized place.”

---

### 🔹 What Do We Mean by “All Data Sources”?

> “When we say data sources, we mean:
>
> * Endpoint logs (CrowdStrike, MDE, Carbon Black)
> * Firewall logs
> * VPN logs
> * Azure AD sign-in logs
> * Cloud logs (Azure, AWS)
> * Server event logs
> * Application logs
>
> It does not matter where the data is stored.”

---

### 🔹 How Sentinel Pulls the Data

> “Sentinel connects to these tools using:
>
> * APIs
> * Built-in connectors
> * Log forwarding
> * Agents
>
> It securely pulls the logs into a centralized data platform.”

---

### 🔹 Real Value – Centralized Visibility

> “Instead of opening five different consoles and switching dashboards,
> Sentinel provides a single investigation pane.
>
> One dashboard.
> One incident view.
> One correlated alert.”

---

### 🔹 Cross-Product Correlation (Very Strong Point)

> “For example, Sentinel can correlate:
>
> A suspicious login from Azure AD
> AND
> A malicious PowerShell execution from MDE
> AND
> An unusual outbound firewall connection
>
> And combine them into one incident.”

That is the power.

---

### 🔹 What SIEM Does

> “As a SIEM, Sentinel:
>
> * Collects logs
> * Stores them
> * Applies analytics rules
> * Detects patterns
> * Generates incidents”

---

### 🔹 What SOAR Does

> “As a SOAR platform, Sentinel can:
>
> * Automatically disable a compromised user
> * Isolate a device in MDE
> * Block an IP in firewall
> * Send alert to Teams
> * Create a ServiceNow ticket
>
> All through automated playbooks.”

---

### 🔹  Closing Line

> “So if our security tools are sensors,
> Microsoft Sentinel is the central brain that connects all signals, correlates them, and orchestrates response across the enterprise.”
